## Summary of the new feature/enhancement

Currently, if you have a deeply nested JSON object and you want to expand one of those nested properties, 
you need to something like this:

(this is for a GraphQL query using the GitHub API)

```ps
$nodes = 
    $query | 
    ConvertFrom-Json | 
    select @{ Name='nodes'; Expression={$_.data.organization.sponsorshipsAsMaintainer.nodes}} | 
    select -ExpandProperty nodes
```

The alternative "normal" way without using `Expression` would be:

```ps
$nodes = 
    $query | 
    ConvertFrom-Json | 
    select -ExpandProperty data |
    select -ExpandProperty organization |
    select -ExpandProperty sponsorshipsAsMaintainer |
    select -ExpandProperty nodes
```

So, when using deeply nested JSON responses from web APIs, a more convenient syntax for 
expanding would be highly desirable to make for more concise code.

<details><summary>Example JSON $query</summary>

```json
{
  "data": {
    "organization": {
      "sponsorshipsAsMaintainer": {
        "nodes": [
          {
            "sponsorEntity": {
              "id": "...",
            },
            "tier": {
              "monthlyPriceInDollars": 1
            }
          },
          {
            "sponsorEntity": {
              "id": "...",
            },
            "tier": {
              "monthlyPriceInDollars": 2
            }
          },
          {
            "sponsorEntity": {
              "id": "...",
            },
            "tier": {
              "monthlyPriceInDollars": 5
            }
          }
        ],
        "pageInfo": {
          "hasNextPage": false,
          "endCursor": "asdfasdf"
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

</details>

## Proposed technical implementation details

I can see two potential implementations: 

1. Extend existing `-ExpandProperty` to interpret dotted property name automatically:

```ps
$nodes = 
    $query | 
    ConvertFrom-Json | 
    select -ExpandProperty data.organization.sponsorshipsAsMaintainer.nodes
```

2. Introduce a new `-ExpandPropertyExpression` instead:

```ps
$nodes = 
    $query | 
    ConvertFrom-Json | 
    select -ExpandPropertyExpression data.organization.sponsorshipsAsMaintainer.nodes
```

Both would result in `$nodes` containing the expanded sub-property of the graph, just like the equivalent long-form `-ExpandProperty` shown above.

### Describe the bug
I try to migrate my web API from framework to .NET 5. I have some code to get UUID via PowerShell
```
var script = @"$computerSystemProduct = Get-WmiObject -class Win32_ComputerSystemProduct -namespace root\CIMV2 
                    $computerSystemProduct.UUID";
```
in the framework version, it works fine, but in .NET 5 version, I've got null in the result and an error
The 'Get-WmiObject' command was found in the module 'Microsoft.PowerShell.Management', but the module could not be loaded. For more information, run 'Import-Module Microsoft.PowerShell.Management'.

I use PowerShell from System.Management.Automation In both API
I've tried to change the script to 
```
            var script = @"Import-Module Microsoft.PowerShell.Management
                    $computerSystemProduct = Get-WmiObject -class Win32_ComputerSystemProduct -namespace root\CIMV2 
                    $computerSystemProduct.UUID";
```
but get the same result.

### To Reproduce
 var script = @"$computerSystemProduct = Get-WmiObject -class Win32_ComputerSystemProduct -namespace root\CIMV2 
                    $computerSystemProduct.UUID";
using (PowerShell ps = PowerShell.Create())
            {
                ps.AddScript(script);

                var pipelineObjects = await ps.InvokeAsync().ConfigureAwait(false);

                var result = pipelineObjects.FirstOrDefault()?.BaseObject?.ToString();
                var errors = ps.Streams.Error.ReadAll();
                return result;
            }

### Exceptions (if any)
No exception, an error in ps.Streams.Error.ReadAll()

### Further technical details
- .NET 5
- Wndows 8, x64
- VS 2019

